00:47:31.880 --> 00:47:33.752
So from a meta
design standpoint,

00:47:33.752 --> 00:47:35.728
if you wanted to make
tools for game designers,

00:47:35.728 --> 00:47:37.300
what advice would you have?

00:47:37.300 --> 00:47:38.675
CAROLYN VANESELTINE:
The question

00:47:38.675 --> 00:47:40.780
was, from a meta
perspective, what

00:47:40.780 --> 00:47:44.510
would be my advice to
people who want to make game

00:47:44.510 --> 00:47:48.700
engines for non-programmers.

00:47:48.700 --> 00:47:51.200
This is actually a really
interesting question for me,

00:47:51.200 --> 00:47:54.860
because one of the things that
I've been working on quietly

00:47:54.860 --> 00:47:58.580
behind the scenes has
been exactly that.

00:47:58.580 --> 00:48:01.630
There are reasons why
I wanted to learn C#.

00:48:01.630 --> 00:48:03.470
The thing that I
would say is most

00:48:03.470 --> 00:48:07.990
important to keep in mind
is that you want to minimize

00:48:07.990 --> 00:48:11.210
the number of walls that
people can run into,

00:48:11.210 --> 00:48:15.850
that if it's possible
to keep people

00:48:15.850 --> 00:48:18.950
from using bad syntax, for
whatever the system is,

00:48:18.950 --> 00:48:20.380
keep them from doing that.

00:48:20.380 --> 00:48:23.000
Make it impossible to
make bad decisions.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:25.580
Make it possible to make
interesting decisions.

00:48:25.580 --> 00:48:28.120
And I recognize
that it's very hard

00:48:28.120 --> 00:48:30.730
to get rid of runtime
errors, like, you

00:48:30.730 --> 00:48:33.490
can't help the people who go
and divide by zero deliberately.

00:48:33.490 --> 00:48:36.440
Yes, you divided by zero and
now everything is going to stop.

00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:38.990
But if it's not
possible for them

00:48:38.990 --> 00:48:42.940
to hit go and then have compiler
errora after compiler error

00:48:42.940 --> 00:48:46.720
fter compiler error, if it
will run but give them a heads

00:48:46.720 --> 00:48:50.100
up about what went wrong,
that would be my advice.

00:48:50.100 --> 00:48:54.440
Make it as streamlined as
possible to make something.

00:48:54.440 --> 00:48:58.100
I also want to give credit
to Chris Klimas, who

00:48:58.100 --> 00:49:02.600
is the creator of Twine,
who was looking specifically

00:49:02.600 --> 00:49:04.503
at this kind of question
when he created it.

00:49:07.890 --> 00:49:08.854
Anybody else?

00:49:12.449 --> 00:49:13.990
AUDIENCE: So I have
a question that's

00:49:13.990 --> 00:49:17.170
a little bit of a
tangent from your talk,

00:49:17.170 --> 00:49:19.184
goes a little bit
beyond game design.

00:49:19.184 --> 00:49:21.600
The thing I find really neat
about what you've been saying

00:49:21.600 --> 00:49:25.672
has been the-- I guess I'll say
the bridge between programmers

00:49:25.672 --> 00:49:27.630
and non-programmers in
the field of game design

00:49:27.630 --> 00:49:31.090
that's been created by these
different systems where you can

00:49:31.090 --> 00:49:32.620
actually do some game design.

00:49:32.620 --> 00:49:34.203
And I think of these
different systems

00:49:34.203 --> 00:49:39.021
as providing different ways to
express programming logic that

00:49:39.021 --> 00:49:41.270
are somewhat more intuitive
to people who haven't gone

00:49:41.270 --> 00:49:43.170
through the, OK, let's learn
Assembler from scratch,

00:49:43.170 --> 00:49:45.086
and all right, this is
how the computer thinks

00:49:45.086 --> 00:49:46.410
and that kind of stuff.

00:49:46.410 --> 00:49:49.179
And I'm sort of wondering,
how do we expand that

00:49:49.179 --> 00:49:49.970
beyond game design?

00:49:49.970 --> 00:49:51.490
Because you said, should
everyone learn to program?

00:49:51.490 --> 00:49:51.990
No.

00:49:51.990 --> 00:49:54.770
And I certainly sympathize
with the feelings behind that.

00:49:54.770 --> 00:49:55.940
There are people who
can't learn to program.

00:49:55.940 --> 00:49:58.065
There are people for whom
it's really not worth it,

00:49:58.065 --> 00:50:00.490
and they will not enjoy it
and they will be miserable.

00:50:00.490 --> 00:50:03.210
But our society is
more and more one

00:50:03.210 --> 00:50:07.150
that's like, just, the computers
are accumulating under our feet

00:50:07.150 --> 00:50:08.580
and we're being
risen up by them.

00:50:08.580 --> 00:50:10.120
And for the people who
don't understand anything

00:50:10.120 --> 00:50:12.730
about programming, don't
understand how computers work,

00:50:12.730 --> 00:50:14.340
I think the feeling
is just being

00:50:14.340 --> 00:50:18.480
more and more helpless in the
face of all sorts of stuff

00:50:18.480 --> 00:50:19.570
around them.

00:50:19.570 --> 00:50:23.380
So I'd love to see that bridge
that you're building in game

00:50:23.380 --> 00:50:25.014
design outside of game design.

00:50:25.014 --> 00:50:26.430
Do you know of any
efforts in that

00:50:26.430 --> 00:50:29.350
area, ways to make, I'll
say programming in general--

00:50:29.350 --> 00:50:32.250
although, wow, is that
broad statement-- more

00:50:32.250 --> 00:50:34.810
accessible to people
who aren't programmers?

