00:53:38.410 --> 00:53:41.480
Anybody else?

00:53:41.480 --> 00:53:44.170
AUDIENCE: So I had a general
question about building tools.

00:53:44.170 --> 00:53:46.710
So in some sense, building a
game with a restricted language

00:53:46.710 --> 00:53:48.418
is like building a
very specialized tool.

00:53:48.418 --> 00:53:51.437
So for mechanical things, you
can build either a hammer,

00:53:51.437 --> 00:53:53.020
and a hammer is very
good at hammering

00:53:53.020 --> 00:53:54.237
but terrible at other things.

00:53:54.237 --> 00:53:56.070
And their other tools
are Swiss army knives,

00:53:56.070 --> 00:53:58.510
which are kind of expert use.

00:53:58.510 --> 00:53:59.905
So I've seen this
in game engines

00:53:59.905 --> 00:54:01.030
that you try to build, too.

00:54:01.030 --> 00:54:01.870
This is a tool.

00:54:01.870 --> 00:54:03.456
It knows how to
speak certain things,

00:54:03.456 --> 00:54:05.080
but it's extremely
frustrating when you

00:54:05.080 --> 00:54:06.950
try to go beyond that paradigm.

00:54:06.950 --> 00:54:08.533
And I don't know if
you can talk a bit

00:54:08.533 --> 00:54:10.510
about that trade-off
between generalized tools

00:54:10.510 --> 00:54:11.740
and specialized tools.

00:54:11.740 --> 00:54:13.210
CAROLYN VANESELTINE: Certainly.

00:54:13.210 --> 00:54:18.150
So that's something that we see
with choice scripts, RPG Maker,

00:54:18.150 --> 00:54:20.370
Adventure Game Studio, Ren'Py.

00:54:20.370 --> 00:54:22.980
They are aimed very
specifically at doing

00:54:22.980 --> 00:54:25.420
one specific kind of game.

00:54:25.420 --> 00:54:28.666
And once you branch
off that, it's

00:54:28.666 --> 00:54:31.610
that question of making
sure that the system you're

00:54:31.610 --> 00:54:34.390
using to make what
you're making actually

00:54:34.390 --> 00:54:36.670
fits with what you're
trying to make.

00:54:36.670 --> 00:54:38.740
And I got rescued by
a programmer once,

00:54:38.740 --> 00:54:43.110
about a year ago, because
I had this great idea

00:54:43.110 --> 00:54:47.900
for an asynchronous multiplayer
game written in Inform 7.

00:54:47.900 --> 00:54:51.870
And I knew that Inform
7 can support data that

00:54:51.870 --> 00:54:53.990
holds over from play to play.

00:54:53.990 --> 00:54:57.919
And I thought to myself, I can
make a game that's multiplayer

00:54:57.919 --> 00:55:00.210
where multiple people can
play it and affect each other

00:55:00.210 --> 00:55:02.970
by just putting it on a server.

00:55:02.970 --> 00:55:04.649
I didn't understand
what was going

00:55:04.649 --> 00:55:06.940
to happen was that it was
going to cache in the browser

00:55:06.940 --> 00:55:10.060
and people would not be able
to interact with each other.

00:55:10.060 --> 00:55:12.110
I didn't understand
the limits of my tool.

00:55:12.110 --> 00:55:14.360
I wound up-- and this
was for a game jam--

00:55:14.360 --> 00:55:17.110
so I wound up running,
actually, to my fiance,

00:55:17.110 --> 00:55:20.800
Danielle Church, who
is extraordinarily good

00:55:20.800 --> 00:55:23.810
at programming,
and said, save me.

00:55:23.810 --> 00:55:27.360
I have created an idea
that is beyond my toolset.

00:55:27.360 --> 00:55:31.340
And she set up server
communication and JavaScript,

00:55:31.340 --> 00:55:33.350
and made it so that
it could actually

00:55:33.350 --> 00:55:36.310
happen the way I had
originally pictured it.

00:55:36.310 --> 00:55:36.970
Yes.

